\section{Comprehensive Notes: Von Neumann Architecture}

The Von Neumann architecture is the foundation of modern computing. Its defining feature is the \textbf{stored program concept}: both the instructions (the program) and the data required by those instructions are stored in the \textit{same} primary memory (RAM), and are fetched sequentially.

\subsection{The CPU and its Components}
The CPU acts as the brain of the computer. It contains several distinct internal components:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Control Unit (CU):} Manages the execution of instructions. It sends control signals to other components to coordinate the fetch-decode-execute cycle.
    \item \textbf{Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU):} Performs all mathematical calculations (e.g., addition) and logical comparisons (e.g., AND, OR, greater than).
\end{itemize}

\begin{stratbox}
When asked for the "purpose of the CPU," do not just write "to process data." The exact Cambridge-approved phrase is: \textbf{"To process data and instructions by executing the Fetch-Decode-Execute cycle."}
\end{stratbox}

\subsection{Special Purpose Registers}
Registers are tiny, extremely fast memory locations located \textit{directly inside} the CPU. 

\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.5}
\noindent
\begin{tabularx}{\textwidth}{@{} l l X @{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Register} & \textbf{Name} & \textbf{Specific Role} \\
\midrule
\textbf{PC} & Program Counter & Holds the address of the \textit{next} instruction to be fetched. \\
\textbf{MAR} & Memory Address Reg. & Holds the address of the memory location currently being read from or written to. \\
\textbf{MDR} & Memory Data Reg. & Holds the actual data or instruction that has just been fetched from memory, or is about to be written to memory. \\
\textbf{CIR} & Current Instruction Reg. & Holds the instruction that is currently being decoded and executed. \\
\textbf{ACC} & Accumulator & Stores the results of calculations carried out by the ALU. \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\vspace{0.4cm}

\begin{errortrap}
A very common mistake is confusing the MAR and the MDR. Remember: The MAR holds the \textbf{location} (where we are looking), and the MDR holds the \textbf{contents} (what we actually found there). 
\end{errortrap}

\subsection{System Buses}
Buses are sets of parallel wires connecting the CPU to Memory and I/O devices.
