\section{In-Class Practice Worksheet}

\noindent\textbf{Question 1: Architecture \& Processing (11 Marks)}\\
A smartphone uses a central processing unit based on the Von Neumann model.
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*, label=(\alph*)]
    \item Describe the stored program concept as it applies to this smartphone. \textit{[2 marks]}
    \item Identify the THREE buses that connect the processor to main memory, and state the direction of data flow for each. \textit{[6 marks]}
    \item Explain the specific role of the Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU) when a user plays a 3D mobile game. \textit{[3 marks]}
\end{enumerate}

\vspace{0.4cm}
\noindent\textbf{Question 2: The Fetch-Decode-Execute Cycle (12 Marks)}\\
An automated ticket machine at a train station uses a microprocessor. The machine scans barcodes, calculates fares, and prints tickets.
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*, label=(\alph*)]
    \item Describe the sequence of events that occurs in the registers during the \textbf{fetch} stage of the FDE cycle. \textit{[5 marks]}
    \item Explain the difference in purpose between the Memory Address Register (MAR) and the Memory Data Register (MDR). \textit{[4 marks]}
    \item During the execution stage, the machine calculates the total fare. Identify which register will store the final result of this calculation, and state which component performed the calculation. \textit{[3 marks]}
\end{enumerate}

\vspace{0.4cm}
\noindent\textbf{Question 3: Memory \& I/O Concepts (11 Marks)}\\
A smart thermostat records room temperature every minute and adjusts a heating valve accordingly.
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*, label=(\alph*)]
    \item The thermostat contains both RAM and ROM. State TWO characteristics of ROM. \textit{[2 marks]}
    \item Explain why the smart thermostat requires both RAM and ROM to function correctly. \textit{[4 marks]}
    \item A sensor detects the temperature and sends an interrupt signal to the processor. Describe how the processor handles this interrupt. \textit{[5 marks]}
\end{enumerate}

